posts.title: Restored 1948 Transition Model 70
posts.text:
Two years back I posted my efforts in restoration of a model 70 mfg in 1948 with the dolls head tang.
The rifle had been well used and the stock was beaten up pretty much beyond use. I made a new stock and decided to have the pancake cheek piece found on the '48 period Super Grade. It was pointed out to me that the standard grade did not have such a scope cheek piece till later in the 50's and was not true to the restoration. None the less, since I had already formed it and was in the process of fitting it to the barrel and receiver, I went ahead and finished it.
Though I had planned on re-blueing it, after considering the forum advice on leaving the blueing on the rifle as-is and not do a re-blue, I decided to leave it as it was. All things considered, it worked out pretty well.
The result was very satisfying and if I do say so, not a bad job. So much so that I'm paranoid now about taking out and shooting lest I somehow damage untold months of work.
So, I thought I'd ask the experts if you know of a drop-in stock for a transition model 70? I checked with boyd's and they have a pre-war II stock but cannot be sure it would fit a '48 transition. I thought I'd poll you all to see if anyone has found a composite or artificial material stock that was a drop in for a transition model with the dolls head tang?
I'd like for a drop in 'cause I've already got two major projects I'm 30% into and I need another fit and finish job like rocks in my head.
Advice and wisdom is appreciated.
Ken

Doxorubicin is the generic drug name for anti-cancer chemotherapy drug Adriamycin and Rubex. Doxorubicin is an anthracycline antibiotic and belongs to the group of anti-cancer medication known as antineoplastic and is made from the natural product produced by bacterium Streptomyces peucetius var. caesius. It is used for the treatment of different types of cancer including breast, stomach, ovary, bone, testicles, bladder, lung, soft tissue, osteogenic sarcoma, Wilms’ tumor, and Hodgkin’s and non-Hodgkin’s lymphomas. It is also used less commonly in the treatment of squamous cell carcinomas of the head and neck. Vagina and cervix, refractory multiple myeloma, and neuroblastoma. Doxorubicin inhibits and or slows the rate of proliferation of cancerous cells by intercalating between the base pairs in the DNA helix, thereby preventing DNA replication and inhibiting protein synthesis. This medication is available in injection solution and lyophilized powder form and is administered intravenously either through peripheral inserted central line catheters (PICC) or central venous catheters (CVC). The dosage of this medication depends on the type and severity of cancer, and type of other medication used during treatments and is most commonly scheduled at 21 days of every dosage.

posts.title: A Mysterious Cavern
posts.text:
DeviantArt Related / Devious Fun / Other 
There was a blast of blue light that lit up the entire clearing; one that made Donner have to close his eyes to avoid being blinded. When it all cleared, Donner opened his eyes to see Warlock standing beside Dasher, he wolf yelping as it ran back into the forest. 
Sick with worry, Donner leapt quickly forward towards his two friends, stumbling once or twice in the snow as he went. “Dasher!” He cried, whinnying nervously. “Are you alright?” 
Dasher was breathing heavily, steam rising off his sides because of the heat. He snorted tiredly in reply. “I’ll be fine.” 
“We need to get out of this forest,” Warlock muttered, thankful that Dasher hadn’t gotten hurt. It was clear that the wolves were ravenous, and a flighty reindeer, a reindeer who’d gotten himself stuck in a tree previously and a magically drained unicorn would be easy picking. 
Donner and Dasher both nodded eagerly in agreement, the three continuing through the woods. The scent of fire, wolf and sweat still lingered in Warlock’s nostrils, a combination of scents that made him uncomfortable. 
Exhausted of his magic, Warlock didn’t know which way they were going. If they kept walking, they should reach the edge of the forest at some point, but Warlock was scared of what danger they might face if they wandered deeper into the woods. He didn’t want another run in with those wolves, and by the way Dasher was glancing around nervously for any sight of those golden eyes, he didn’t either. 
Donner looked tired, icy blue eyes weary in the darkness. Warlock was beginning to feel tired himself, and knew that if he hadn’t found these two reindeer he’d be fast asleep in a little hollow somewhere, safe, but these two would be wolf fodder. He’d much rather save the lives of two young, mysterious and confusing reindeer unicorn creatures than get a full night’s rest. 
And so they plodded on. Warlock’s legs felt like they were made out of lead, heavy and limp with the snow dragging them down further. The two reindeer seemed to have a bit more agility in the snow, lucky for them. 
It was about an hour later when Warlock saw the edge of the forest up ahead, and the snowy, grassy plain he knew in front. He gave a happy whinny of joy at seeing the area, charging forward. The two reindeer neighed joyously as well, plunging after their unicorn friend and out of the trees. 
The plain was a beautiful place at night. The moon hung high in the sky, shining brightly when not obscured by the grey clouds that drifted across, sprinkling the ground with snow as they went. The sky was a darkened blue, stars scattered across it like glitter, the light of the moon illuminating the space. It was empty apart from the three steeds, no signs of other life at all. 
The once grassy plain was a place Warlock knew well. Herds dwelled here often for its sweet grass and open space, herds which Warlock would sometimes converse with on his travels. He knew most of the good hiding spots and ones that would be safe for the night. 
The side of a mountain bordered the plain, the base of it surrounded by bushes and other undergrowth. Warlock knew that there was a small cavern there that should be safe to shelter in for the night. 
“There’s a cavern in those bushes over there, we can stay there,” Warlock explained to his tired friends, who gave nods of happiness at the thought of being able to finally rest. 
Together they journeyed over, taking it slower this time. When they finally got there, Warlock lit a flame to guide their way into the otherwise empty tunnel. 
It was cold, but enclosed and had a roof. The floor was made out of a damp limestone, their hooves clopping on it as they entered. Warlock had to duck his head slightly to avoid clipping his horn on the roof. 
The two reindeer collapsed as soon as they were inside, huddled up against each other for warmth. Donner looked over to Warlock, nickering and tossing his head in an invitation. Warlock lay down beside them, thankful for their warmth. 
It wasn’t long before exhaustion crept over the three, and they drifted off into a deep sleep.
